segments.text: And all of us in a group would walk wherever the party was.
For instance, one night we met down here on Texas Avenue, I guess that's about 33rd Street, and walked out to home, not down by where I was born, a couple of blocks beyond, in a group.
And then we all walked back to that same house and then made it around the very home where the girl lived.
It wasn't any of them to spend the night.
I was accustomed with that girl.
I usually met her at the girl's house.
And we always had a class party every year in school, grade school.
different homes around, but I was there, of course, they were afternoon parties.
How about birthday parties, Mac, in those days?
Was that just a family affair, or would you have... No, they'd have big men, big birthday parties.
That was a big thing.
And, uh... Yeah, a dancing teacher came in, set up a class,
I guess that was long, about 1913.
That was the first one I ever heard of.
My mother put me in the class.
I was the only boy, about 14 girls.
Well, did you enjoy it?
Hell no.
She whipped me every day before I agreed to go.
Sometimes you'd have to crawl along.
But they was a girl just about right for me, and they paired us.
And I felt sorry for her because she had to dance with me every class, the whole thing.
No changing around.
Of course, what we enjoyed most in those days, they had a skating rink way down on Washington Street.
That was a real attraction.
We enjoyed that much more than trying to dance.
We started at that maybe, well, I guess I was five years old when I started going there to skate.
And it continued, and lots of grown people, all ages.
My mother was a wonderful skater.
Did they have shoe skates in those days?
Yeah.
The whole unit together, or just the clamp-ons?
They had them.
Oh, they clamped on.
That was the only kind they had.
Oh.
Well, those others, they had the ice skates.
Well, they have some roller skate now that are the shoe and everything all together.
Well, it's been so long.
The tees, they fit you.
You wore you right in the shoes.
My mother, as I say, was a wonderful skater.
My father was clubbed in his hands.
He didn't bust his ass.
What are you talking about?
That's all right.
Why he didn't break himself, all the pieces, I'll never know.
But all ages can.
That's pretty interesting.

Getting back away from the social activities a little bit, and right about the time of the First World War, speaking of, or just before, they were building locks out here on the river for river navigation, I understand.
Well, that was quite... What did you think about that, or what did the people think about that?
That was much farther back.
They were going to make the Pazos River navigable to what the port was so they could compete with Galveston.
They wanted to.

take it all the way up to beyond wake who i think it's so much closer down as important was and then they tried to start work on on the trinity river we never did what but they put in a lock and down as they call it they put in several along i noticed one by her
It was called Port Sullivan.
And they had one down just this side of Navasota.
Well, up in those days at Port Sullivan, could you see anything of the buildings that had been there at one time?
Was Port Sullivan really still in existence then?
It had been abandoned.
But it's right close to Valley Junction, you see.
That's where you change cars.
the Southern Pacific to go to Houston if you wanted to go on the R&G end.
And then from the R&G end came from Austin and San Antonio to Diamond Junction and change that to go to Houston or Diamond.
See, there's a nice little great garden.
The real, the main road was from
I went to San Antonio, St. Louis.
I went to Austin.
I went to Austin, Palestine.
I didn't go to Dallas or Fort Worth.
I missed one in Brown.
In Brown, I went to Spur.
I went down to Houston.
to Valley Junction.
How about after World War II, the main agricultural business was still counting in the area?
You mean World War I?
World War I, I beg your pardon.
It continued to be that.
only cash crop until Roosevelt's administration when he put in the farm program and paid people not to raise cotton and corn and encouraged them to get into the cattle and grain solvent business.
That's when you had the development of grain solvents and also your livestock in this country.
Up to that time, they didn't have any improved pastures.
They just had old common crossbred cattle.
Nobody had any good cattle.
And that, you know, Brazos County land is probably the poorest in the state, the natural land.
It's either blow sand or hard pastures.
One of the two.
But since that time, in the early 30s, they have been improving the land so much that it's real good for grazing.
It never was intended for cotton.
But when I was a boy, they planted cotton to the fence.
And they planted just enough corn to feed their own cattle.
And, of course, everything was farmed by mules, most of the mule feed.
Now, of course, they had a few horses to ride.
The more affluent had buckets.
Some had celery.
We had a
horse and buggy when I was a child.
Kept that until about 19.
I guess 15.
Well, the Lawrence family seems to have stayed in a pretty high position of affluence throughout.
I don't know much about the Howells.
The Howells?
The Howell family you mentioned?
I'm not sure about it.
Well, no, actually, the Lawrence family has always been just able to get by and scratch like hell, always in a bind.
The Howells were the richest family in the Bronx.
They owned everything.
They even got into retail grocery business.
And then...
They got into wholesale grocery business.
Howling Company did every bit as much, maybe a little more business than Lawrence Grocers Company.
And that was just one of their interests.
Lawrence Grocers Company, that was my father's main interest, almost.
Well, he had a little interest for almost a long time.
And that was a frustration.
for a long time before he acquired control of the stock market.
So after he started out, he owned about 40% of it.
Maybe not quite that many.
Well?
In fact, he never did acquire control in his own name, but in the 20s,
I wanted to sell his stock.
My father recommended that I buy it, and I did.
That gave us control of the two of us.
Well, we had $102,000 worth of stock and $200,000 worth of corporation.
That's the control we had.
The Howells had nobody else interested in the family.
the old gentleman and his three sons.
What's happened to the Howell family since then?
Well, they've all died out, and the only one who has left married a Navasota girl, and he moved down there and operated the lumberyard down there for a long time.
sold his interest down there and then moved back here.
But he's always been retired.
Now, he's an unusually well-fixed man himself.
He inherited a lot of money.
He made a lot of money.
But his wife was four more than he is.
She's now a soldier.
Her father was a doctor down there.
He made a hell of a lot of money and died.
Her mother.
Is this going on the record?
John, this will just be reviewed by graduate students.
Well, no, Douglas.
By mature people.
You know, you can use any kind of language you want.
Douglas and I, we were raised with it.
He's raised where the city national bank is now.
We played together.
He's less than a year older than I am.
But anyhow, his wife wasn't born here.
She owned land down there around Nalasota.
He inherited a lot of land here around Bob.
Like I said, he's made a lot of money himself, but he inherited it.
John, can you tell us a little bit about your mother a little more?
More or less what she used to do, how she kept the house, not whether she kept it well, I'm sure, but did she have servants helping her?
What kind of good food did she make for you?
Well, at the start, she didn't have any help.
Me and my father married, they didn't have any help at all.
But then after we moved down on by the first bank here now, she began to keep cooking, as we called it.
And she always managed to have a good one.
But my mother was a wonderful cook and homemaker.
And she'd take those niggers with no training at all, just no time at all.
She'd make them into wonderful cooks.
and servants, and they could serve the table and everything.
Do you remember any special foods that we used to cook then or prepare then that we don't nowadays?
Or let's say, what was your favorite?
Well, my favorite always was meat and bread and rice and gravy and potatoes.
But my mother had gone to a convent when she was a child,
And they had a rule that everybody had to eat some of everything on the table.
And my mother took that into effect too for me, but of course she couldn't make my father eat it.
And she believed in lots of different vegetables all the time.
And as a result, I had to eat some of everything that was put on, even if it was just a teaspoon for her.
But as a result, I acquired a taste for most everything.
And I like everything now except squash.
My mother, for some reason, didn't serve squash, and I didn't like to eat it, and my wife had me there, and she begged me to let her.
John, where did you meet your wife?
At the University of Texas.
At the University of Texas.
In fact...
My father said she's on the most wild thing I brought home from university or anything.
He was crazy about it.
But she was from Palestine.
Of course, we married in 1920 and have lived here ever since.
She feels like she's from Gaza.
And you have a son, I gather, the lawyer?
Yes, we have just the one child now.
We had a daughter, but we lost her at 72 at age 44.
But she had three children, and my son had two.
So we have five grandchildren.
Wow.
Only one of them lives in Brown.
That's the youngest.
She's still in high school.
But one of my granddaughters married a man who lives down in the bottom.
She teaches school here in Brown.
But we see her quite often.
One of our grandsons is in Dallas.
The other grandson is in Rua Dolce, New Mexico.
The other granddaughter lives in Denton.
No great-grandchildren yet?
I'm about given up.
This granddaughter teaches and has been married six years.
This grandson lives in Dallas and has been married two and a half years.
And my granddaughter that lives in Denver was married about four years before she got a divorce.
She was single.
So with that much exposure and no very grandchildren, I don't know that I'll ever have it.
Well, we'll keep open, waiting.
John, there is one item I forgot to ask that I know over in Brenham around First World War.
I guess they're

lot of anti-german feelings in the in a german community or there's a lot of mixtures did they have this problem here were there a number of german people here that were getting into i thought we were getting into the wrong war we had some in 19 18 17 and 18 but very lovely there was
Most of those people were loyal Americans, and they explained that.
Now, some of those other counties, people of German extraction, they had quite a bit of feeling.
We had lots of Italians here.
And in World War II, there was some feeling that they were all loyal Americans.
John, do you remember, there are, of course, quite a few prominent Italians in the community now.
Do you remember when these Italian families first began moving into here?
And did they come in with money, or did they just... No, most of them came in, came from the old country, as they called it, and steerage, and they made their way.
Sidon...

ones uh did well they worked hard they're the hardest working people that there is and that's the problem that made the order for them and as they had become affluent and could they would send money back and bring others over and help them get started maybe work them themselves maybe rent them a little land
help them get credit to make a crop.
And then they'd bring the, if they were already married, they'd bring the married wives over, the children.
Some of them brought the girls, the sweethearts over and married here.
But they all worked.
And then I chose this Beresko family.
That's a case in point.
And a man built up substantial means for old man Tony Beresko over here and helped him get established.
And he brought his family over and started them out.
This brother, Floresco, who was an outstanding man, he came over with his mother in the steerage, joined his father.
He made quite a bit of money on his own.
The whole family now, all of those children did well.
I suppose as a president of the bank, you saw a lot of development here in Bryan, economic development, a lot of success stories.
I thought maybe we'll take a break just for a moment here.
But I wanted to ask you, if you were talking to your great-grandson someday,
what advice that you'd give to him to succeed in life and to, as well as economically, just to be a good person and a good citizen?
I tell you, I told my children and grandchildren, first, keep the very best company possible.
Second, choose a worthy objective, a challenge.
Third, work at it hard.
and live for the best things in life.
Well, that seems like mighty fine advice.
Well, it is the best I ever was, even if it isn't mine.
Well, John, is there anything that you can think that you'd like to take that you might be especially interested in other people hearing about?
Well, I think first that what development, and it seems phenomenal to me, is due to the economic thrust provided by Texas A&M.
And second, Brown and College Station were both, you might say, blessed with good substantial
ambitious people who were able to benefit from that economic thrust.
And although there were two factions here and two factions at A&M, those factions worked together and competing with each other they brought out the best in each other.
And so
different factions pool their resources to develop businesses really worthwhile.
For instance, the banks and then this building in Long Hill was organized in 1919.
Of course, it's been a tremendous success.
It was organized as a chamber of commerce project, and both factions supported it.
Now, they each had a bank.
There was a third bank of people that didn't belong to either faction, but all three banks worked for this association.
and due to the economic thrust provided by A&M, it grew to its present size.
John Beck, how do you think Brian fared during the Great Depression of 29?
Well, it was one of the bright spots in the nation.
We thought we had it rough, but we didn't have it bad.
We didn't have a bank failure.
We had practically no business failure.
We had very little unemployment.
So you think it did generally better than probably most of the rest of the country?
Well, with the exception of Boston, it was the best town in Texas.
Of course, it was due to that tax money.
That's what kept Boston so good.
No doubt about that.
But those people out there, they didn't get a cut until 1935 or something when they were beginning to come out of the Depression.
And they cut those people's salaries.
But in the meantime, they kept this town going.
That's interesting.
You know, you retired, I think, at about the time that the air base closed out here.
Is that true?
Somewhere near that?
Oh, I stayed on a while after they had closed.
And I just wondered whether there was any excitement about the base closing and panic selling.
Oh, yes.
People cried out that we were ruined.
No, it seems like it's grown tremendously since then.
Yes, a little bit.
It kept going.
But it didn't affect us.
It was a big thing, but it didn't compare with what Texas A&M did.
But then in the 50s, we began to develop some industry here.
Well, up to that time, all we had was a cotton warehouse and compress
oil mill, and then they began to bring in this industry.
Now that's a major contributor to the economic situation.
You think that's pretty good for the town?
Yes, it's good.
Keep developing.
Take this old line coal, send a knife, no furniture, no
New businesses out on the west bypass.
They employ lots of people.
And they were all located here because of the proximity to Texas A&M.
In order to be able to take care of that, or take advantage of that research foundation.
That's why International Shoe came in here.
Lenko came in here because All Britain was a graduate of A&M, and he had so much labor trouble in Houston, he had to move around.
So he moved, he chose Brown because of his love for A&M.
That's quite a bonus.
Of course, then it's obvious that A&M played a pretty big role here in the community.
But people on the right that
the importance of that research foundation.
They give credit to the extension service and the experiment station, and I'm certainly not taking anything away from them.
They do a whole lot.
That research foundation does a whole lot more than it gets credit for.
Well, John, I guess we're just about at the end, unless you have anything more that you'd like to add.
No, I don't know.
Hang on.
I don't know that this would be of any interest to you.
Oh, yeah, this is going to be interesting, but I'll tell you, by tonight, I'll probably think of about 100 questions I wish I would have asked you.
Well, it just so happens I don't have anything to do with it.

you think of something you think yeah if there's some gaps if you wouldn't mind doing it again some some even or you know a little bit more it wouldn't wouldn't take as long as next time to answer a few questions and uh john i'll uh i'm going to have a transcript made of this and i'll bring a copy to you for your own
personal possession, and also, like them, if you'd sign a release, that this tape and that transcript can be used for research purposes at the college.
Well, it's not wrong.
I didn't ask you about any of the houses of prostitution or so forth, or whether you had any in Bryan, but what the economic impact of those was.
